Rye is grown primarily in Eastern, Central and Northern [[Europe]]. The main rye belt stretches from northern [[Germany]] through [[Poland]], [[Ukraine]], [[Belarus]], [[Lithuania]] and [[Latvia]] into central and northern [[Russia]]. Rye is also grown in North America ([[Canada]] and the United States), in South America ([[Argentina]], [[Brazil]] and [[Chile]]), in Oceania ([[Australia]] and [[New Zealand]]), in Turkey, in [[Kazakhstan]] and in northern [[China]].

Production levels of rye have fallen in most of the producing nations, as of 2012. For instance, production of rye in Russia fell from 13.9 million metric tons (t) in 1992 to 2.1 t in 2012. Corresponding figures for other countries are as follows: Poland – falling from 5.9 t in 1992 to 2.9 t in 2005; Germany – 3.3 t to 3.9 t; Belarus – 3.1 t to 1.1 t; China – 1.7 t to 0.7 t.&lt;ref name=&quot;FAO2005&quot;&gt;{{cite web |url = http://www.fao.org/es/ess/top/commodity.html?lang=en&amp;item=71&amp;year=2005 |title = Major Food and Agricultural Commodities and Producers: Countries by Commodity |work = FAO.org |publisher = Food and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations |date = 2005 |access-date = January 8, 2015 }}&lt;/ref&gt;

World trade of rye is low compared with other grains such as wheat. The total export of rye for 2016 was $186M&lt;ref&gt;[http://atlas.media.mit.edu/en/visualize/tree_map/hs92/export/show/all/100200/2016/ OEC - Countries that export Rye (2016)]&lt;/ref&gt; compared with $30.1B for wheat.&lt;ref&gt;[http://atlas.media.mit.edu/en/visualize/tree_map/hs92/export/show/all/100190/2016/ OEC - Countries that export Wheat except durum wheat, and meslin (2016)]&lt;/ref&gt;

Poland consumes the most rye per person at 32.4&amp;nbsp;kg/capita (2009). Nordic and Baltic countries are also very high. The EU in general is around 5.6&amp;nbsp;kg/capita. The entire world only consumes 0.9&amp;nbsp;kg/capita.&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.ryeandhealth.org/statistics-a-usage Statistics and Usage - www.ryeandhealth.org]&lt;/ref&gt;
